import GuideLayout from '../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro';
---
<GuideLayout
  title="Multiple Audio Clips - MAX98357A I2S"
  description="Play multiple audio clips on an ESP32 with a MAX98357A I2S amplifier. Button trigger, auto sequence, and linked playlist modes. Covers clip prep, updated header script, and full sketches."
  toc={[
    {href: '#before-you-start', label: 'Before You Start'},
    {href: '#preparing-clips', label: 'Preparing Your Clips'},
    {href: '#button-mode', label: 'Button Mode'},
    {href: '#auto-sequence', label: 'Auto Sequence'},
    {href: '#linked-sequence', label: 'Linked Sequence'},
    {href: '#troubleshooting', label: 'Troubleshooting'},
  ]}
>

  <div class="hero">
    <div class="category">Audio &bull; ESP32</div>
    <h1>Multiple Audio Clips<br>MAX98357A I2S</h1>
    <div class="meta">
      <div class="meta-item"><strong>Modes:</strong> Button trigger, Auto sequence, Linked playlist</div>
      <div class="meta-item"><strong>Board:</strong> ESP32 Dev Board (38-pin) or ESP32-C3</div>
      <div class="meta-item"><strong>Amp:</strong> MAX98357A</div>
    </div>
    <div class="series-step">MAX98357A I2S Series - Step 3 of 3 - Multiple clips</div>
    <div class="badge badge-wip">&#9881; Under Construction</div>
  </div>

  <!-- Before You Start -->
  <div class="section" id="before-you-start">
    <h2>Before You Start</h2>
    <p>This guide extends the MAX98357A I2S guide. You should already have the amp wired up and a single clip playing before continuing here.</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0.75rem;">This guide covers only what is new: preparing multiple clips with unique variable names, and three sketch modes for triggering playback.</p>
    <div class="callout callout-why">
      <strong>Flash memory budget</strong>
      Three 2-second clips at 44100Hz 16-bit mono = ~517KB of flash. The ESP32 has around 1.2MB available under the Huge APP partition scheme. Plan your clips accordingly - drop to 22050Hz for speech to halve the size per clip.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Preparing Clips -->
  <div class="section" id="preparing-clips">
    <h2>Preparing Your Clips</h2>
    <p>Run the ffmpeg conversion once per clip as in <a href="/guides/max98357a-esp32-audio#preparing-audio" class="term-link">Step 2 - Playing a Clip</a>. Then use the updated script below to convert each WAV to a header file - it takes a third argument for the variable name so each header is unique.</p>

    <h3>New script - wav_to_i2s_header_multi.py</h3>
    <p>Save this as a new file - <code>wav_to_i2s_header_multi.py</code>. It works the same as the script from Step 2 but takes a third argument for the variable name so each header is unique. <a href="/glossary/save-a-script-i2s-multi" class="term-link">How to save a script &rarr;</a></p>
    <div class="code-wrap">
      <pre><code>{`import sys, wave, struct

input_file  = sys.argv[1]
output_file = sys.argv[2]
var_name    = sys.argv[3] if len(sys.argv) > 3 else 'audio'

with wave.open(input_file, 'rb') as f:
    raw = f.readframes(f.getnframes())

samples = struct.unpack('<' + str(len(raw)//2) + 'h', raw)

lines = [
    '#pragma once',
    '#include <pgmspace.h>',
    'const int16_t ' + var_name + '_data[] PROGMEM = {',
]
chunks = [str(s) for s in samples]
for i in range(0, len(chunks), 16):
    lines.append('  ' + ', '.join(chunks[i:i+16]) + ',')
lines.append('};')
lines.append('const size_t ' + var_name + '_len = sizeof(' + var_name + '_data);')

with open(output_file, 'w') as f:
    f.write('\\n'.join(lines) + '\\n')

print('Done: ' + str(len(samples)) + ' samples -> ' + output_file)`}</code></pre>
      <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
    </div>

    <h3>Convert your clips</h3>
    <p>Run once per clip. The third argument sets the variable name used in the sketch. It must be a valid C identifier - letters, numbers, and underscores only, and it cannot start with a number. <code>clip1</code>, <code>beep_short</code>, and <code>alarm2</code> are fine. <code>my clip</code>, <code>hello-world</code>, and <code>1beep</code> are not - they will generate broken C code that won't compile.</p>
    <div class="code-wrap">
      <pre><code>python3 wav_to_i2s_header_multi.py /tmp/clip1_i2s.wav clip1.h clip1</code></pre>
      <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
    </div>
    <p>Repeat for each clip, changing the input file, output header name, and variable name - for example <code>clip2_i2s.wav clip2.h clip2</code>, <code>clip3_i2s.wav clip3.h clip3</code>, and so on.</p>
    <p>Each header defines <code>clip1_data</code> / <code>clip1_len</code>, <code>clip2_data</code> / <code>clip2_len</code>, and so on. Place all <code>.h</code> files in your <a href="/glossary/sketch-folder" class="term-link">sketch folder</a> alongside the <code>.ino</code> file.</p>

    <h3>Batch convert a whole folder</h3>
    <p>If all your source files are in one folder, this shell loop runs ffmpeg and the header script on every WAV in one go. Each <code>.h</code> file is named after its source file automatically.</p>
    <div class="code-wrap">
      <pre><code>{`for f in ~/Downloads/myclips/*.wav; do
  name=$(basename "$f" .wav)
  ffmpeg -y -i "$f" -ar 44100 -ac 1 -acodec pcm_s16le "/tmp/\${name}_i2s.wav"
  python3 ~/wav_to_i2s_header_multi.py "/tmp/\${name}_i2s.wav" "\${name}.h" "$name"
done`}</code></pre>
      <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
    </div>
    <p>Replace <code>~/Downloads/myclips/</code> with the path to your audio folder. The <code>.h</code> files land in your current directory - move them all into your sketch folder alongside the <code>.ino</code> file.</p>
    <div class="callout callout-tip">
      <strong>MP3, M4A, video files?</strong>
      ffmpeg handles any format - just change <code>*.wav</code> to match your files: <code>*.mp3</code>, <code>*.m4a</code>, <code>*.mp4</code>, etc.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Button Mode -->
  <div class="section" id="button-mode">
    <h2>Button Mode</h2>
    <p>Each button press plays the next clip. After the last it loops back to the first. Connect a button between <strong>GPIO18</strong> and <strong>GND</strong> - no resistor needed, the sketch uses the internal pull-up.</p>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Button leg</th><th>ESP32 Dev Board</th><th>ESP32-C3</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>One leg</td><td>GPIO18</td><td>GPIO10</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Other leg</td><td>GND</td><td>GND</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="code-wrap">
      <pre><code>{`/*
 * We stand on the shoulders of giants when we build
 * with knowledge gained from others' efforts.
 * That doesn't make us giants. Be humble.
 * Create with care. Open source is the way.
 *
 * MAX98357A I2S - Multiple Clips, Button Trigger
 * -----------------------------------------------
 * Cycles through audio clips on each button press.
 *
 * Board:   ESP32 Dev Board (38-pin) or ESP32-C3
 * Amp:     MAX98357A
 *
 * Wiring (ESP32 Dev Board):
 *   BCLK -> GPIO27  LRC -> GPIO14  DIN -> GPIO13
 *   Button: GPIO18 -> GND
 *
 * Wiring (ESP32-C3):
 *   BCLK -> GPIO4   LRC -> GPIO5   DIN -> GPIO6
 *   Button: GPIO10 -> GND
 *
 * Open source - MIT Licence
 * Electronic Zoology - field notes from the garage
 * https://electroniczoology.com/guides/max98357a-multiple-clips
 */

#include <driver/i2s.h>
#include "clip1.h"
#include "clip2.h"
#include "clip3.h"

// ESP32 Dev Board (38-pin)
#define I2S_BCLK    27
#define I2S_LRCLK   14
#define I2S_DOUT    13
#define BUTTON_PIN  18
// ESP32-C3 - comment out the four lines above and uncomment these:
//#define I2S_BCLK    4
//#define I2S_LRCLK   5
//#define I2S_DOUT    6
//#define BUTTON_PIN  10

#define SAMPLE_RATE 44100
#define VOLUME      0.8f
#define BUF_SAMPLES 256

int16_t i2s_buf[BUF_SAMPLES * 2];

struct Clip {
  const int16_t* data;
  size_t len;
};

// Add or remove rows to match your clips.
// The name here must match the var_name you used with wav_to_i2s_header.py.
// Also update the #include lines above.
const Clip clips[] = {
  { clip1_data, clip1_len },
  { clip2_data, clip2_len },
  { clip3_data, clip3_len },
};
const int CLIP_COUNT = sizeof(clips) / sizeof(clips[0]);

int currentClip = 0;

void playClip(const Clip& c) {
  size_t total = c.len / sizeof(int16_t);
  size_t written;
  for (size_t pos = 0; pos < total; pos += BUF_SAMPLES) {
    size_t count = min((size_t)BUF_SAMPLES, total - pos);
    for (size_t i = 0; i < count; i++) {
      int16_t s = (int16_t)((int16_t)pgm_read_word(&c.data[pos + i]) * VOLUME);
      i2s_buf[i * 2]     = s;
      i2s_buf[i * 2 + 1] = s;
    }
    i2s_write(I2S_NUM_0, i2s_buf, count * 2 * sizeof(int16_t), &written, portMAX_DELAY);
  }
}

void setup() {
  pinMode(BUTTON_PIN, INPUT_PULLUP);

  i2s_config_t cfg = {
    .mode                 = (i2s_mode_t)(I2S_MODE_MASTER | I2S_MODE_TX),
    .sample_rate          = SAMPLE_RATE,
    .bits_per_sample      = I2S_BITS_PER_SAMPLE_16BIT,
    .channel_format       = I2S_CHANNEL_FMT_RIGHT_LEFT,
    .communication_format = I2S_COMM_FORMAT_STAND_I2S,
    .intr_alloc_flags     = ESP_INTR_FLAG_LEVEL1,
    .dma_buf_count        = 8,
    .dma_buf_len          = 64,
    .use_apll             = false,
    .tx_desc_auto_clear   = true,
  };
  i2s_pin_config_t pins = {
    .bck_io_num   = I2S_BCLK,
    .ws_io_num    = I2S_LRCLK,
    .data_out_num = I2S_DOUT,
    .data_in_num  = I2S_PIN_NO_CHANGE,
  };
  i2s_driver_install(I2S_NUM_0, &cfg, 0, NULL);
  i2s_set_pin(I2S_NUM_0, &pins);
}

void loop() {
  if (digitalRead(BUTTON_PIN) == LOW) {
    delay(30);
    if (digitalRead(BUTTON_PIN) == LOW) {
      playClip(clips[currentClip]);
      currentClip = (currentClip + 1) % CLIP_COUNT;
      while (digitalRead(BUTTON_PIN) == LOW);
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>
      <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Auto Sequence -->
  <div class="section" id="auto-sequence">
    <h2>Auto Sequence</h2>
    <p>Plays every clip in order on boot. No button needed. Move the loop into <code>loop()</code> instead of <code>setup()</code> to repeat forever.</p>
    <div class="code-wrap">
      <pre><code>{`/*
 * We stand on the shoulders of giants when we build
 * with knowledge gained from others' efforts.
 * That doesn't make us giants. Be humble.
 * Create with care. Open source is the way.
 *
 * MAX98357A I2S - Multiple Clips, Auto Sequence
 * -----------------------------------------------
 * Plays all clips in order once on boot.
 *
 * Board:   ESP32 Dev Board (38-pin) or ESP32-C3
 * Amp:     MAX98357A
 *
 * Wiring (ESP32 Dev Board):
 *   BCLK -> GPIO27  LRC -> GPIO14  DIN -> GPIO13
 *
 * Wiring (ESP32-C3):
 *   BCLK -> GPIO4   LRC -> GPIO5   DIN -> GPIO6
 *
 * Open source - MIT Licence
 * Electronic Zoology - field notes from the garage
 * https://electroniczoology.com/guides/max98357a-multiple-clips
 */

#include <driver/i2s.h>
#include "clip1.h"
#include "clip2.h"
#include "clip3.h"

// ESP32 Dev Board (38-pin)
#define I2S_BCLK    27
#define I2S_LRCLK   14
#define I2S_DOUT    13
// ESP32-C3 - comment out the three lines above and uncomment these:
//#define I2S_BCLK    4
//#define I2S_LRCLK   5
//#define I2S_DOUT    6

#define SAMPLE_RATE 44100
#define VOLUME      0.8f
#define BUF_SAMPLES 256

int16_t i2s_buf[BUF_SAMPLES * 2];

struct Clip {
  const int16_t* data;
  size_t len;
};

// Add or remove rows to match your clips.
// The name here must match the var_name you used with wav_to_i2s_header.py.
// Also update the #include lines above.
const Clip clips[] = {
  { clip1_data, clip1_len },
  { clip2_data, clip2_len },
  { clip3_data, clip3_len },
};
const int CLIP_COUNT = sizeof(clips) / sizeof(clips[0]);

void playClip(const Clip& c) {
  size_t total = c.len / sizeof(int16_t);
  size_t written;
  for (size_t pos = 0; pos < total; pos += BUF_SAMPLES) {
    size_t count = min((size_t)BUF_SAMPLES, total - pos);
    for (size_t i = 0; i < count; i++) {
      int16_t s = (int16_t)((int16_t)pgm_read_word(&c.data[pos + i]) * VOLUME);
      i2s_buf[i * 2]     = s;
      i2s_buf[i * 2 + 1] = s;
    }
    i2s_write(I2S_NUM_0, i2s_buf, count * 2 * sizeof(int16_t), &written, portMAX_DELAY);
  }
}

void setup() {
  i2s_config_t cfg = {
    .mode                 = (i2s_mode_t)(I2S_MODE_MASTER | I2S_MODE_TX),
    .sample_rate          = SAMPLE_RATE,
    .bits_per_sample      = I2S_BITS_PER_SAMPLE_16BIT,
    .channel_format       = I2S_CHANNEL_FMT_RIGHT_LEFT,
    .communication_format = I2S_COMM_FORMAT_STAND_I2S,
    .intr_alloc_flags     = ESP_INTR_FLAG_LEVEL1,
    .dma_buf_count        = 8,
    .dma_buf_len          = 64,
    .use_apll             = false,
    .tx_desc_auto_clear   = true,
  };
  i2s_pin_config_t pins = {
    .bck_io_num   = I2S_BCLK,
    .ws_io_num    = I2S_LRCLK,
    .data_out_num = I2S_DOUT,
    .data_in_num  = I2S_PIN_NO_CHANGE,
  };
  i2s_driver_install(I2S_NUM_0, &cfg, 0, NULL);
  i2s_set_pin(I2S_NUM_0, &pins);

  for (int i = 0; i < CLIP_COUNT; i++) {
    playClip(clips[i]);
    delay(500);
  }
}

void loop() { }`}</code></pre>
      <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-tip">
      <strong>Loop continuously?</strong>
      Move the <code>for</code> loop and <code>delay</code> into <code>loop()</code> instead of <code>setup()</code> - the sequence repeats forever.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Linked Sequence -->
  <div class="section" id="linked-sequence">
    <h2>Linked Sequence</h2>
    <p>Define a playlist array to control the exact order - repeat clips, skip some, or build a specific sequence. The <code>clips[]</code> array is indexed from 0.</p>
    <div class="code-wrap">
      <pre><code>{`/*
 * We stand on the shoulders of giants when we build
 * with knowledge gained from others' efforts.
 * That doesn't make us giants. Be humble.
 * Create with care. Open source is the way.
 *
 * MAX98357A I2S - Multiple Clips, Linked Sequence
 * ------------------------------------------------
 * Plays clips in a user-defined playlist order.
 *
 * Board:   ESP32 Dev Board (38-pin) or ESP32-C3
 * Amp:     MAX98357A
 *
 * Wiring (ESP32 Dev Board):
 *   BCLK -> GPIO27  LRC -> GPIO14  DIN -> GPIO13
 *
 * Wiring (ESP32-C3):
 *   BCLK -> GPIO4   LRC -> GPIO5   DIN -> GPIO6
 *
 * Open source - MIT Licence
 * Electronic Zoology - field notes from the garage
 * https://electroniczoology.com/guides/max98357a-multiple-clips
 */

#include <driver/i2s.h>
#include "clip1.h"
#include "clip2.h"
#include "clip3.h"

// ESP32 Dev Board (38-pin)
#define I2S_BCLK    27
#define I2S_LRCLK   14
#define I2S_DOUT    13
// ESP32-C3 - comment out the three lines above and uncomment these:
//#define I2S_BCLK    4
//#define I2S_LRCLK   5
//#define I2S_DOUT    6

#define SAMPLE_RATE 44100
#define VOLUME      0.8f
#define BUF_SAMPLES 256

int16_t i2s_buf[BUF_SAMPLES * 2];

struct Clip {
  const int16_t* data;
  size_t len;
};

// Add or remove rows to match your clips.
// The name here must match the var_name you used with wav_to_i2s_header.py.
// Also update the #include lines above.
const Clip clips[] = {
  { clip1_data, clip1_len },  // index 0
  { clip2_data, clip2_len },  // index 1
  { clip3_data, clip3_len },  // index 2
};

// edit this to set the playback order - repeat indices to replay a clip
const int playlist[]   = { 0, 1, 0, 2, 1 };
const int PLAYLIST_LEN = sizeof(playlist) / sizeof(playlist[0]);

void playClip(const Clip& c) {
  size_t total = c.len / sizeof(int16_t);
  size_t written;
  for (size_t pos = 0; pos < total; pos += BUF_SAMPLES) {
    size_t count = min((size_t)BUF_SAMPLES, total - pos);
    for (size_t i = 0; i < count; i++) {
      int16_t s = (int16_t)((int16_t)pgm_read_word(&c.data[pos + i]) * VOLUME);
      i2s_buf[i * 2]     = s;
      i2s_buf[i * 2 + 1] = s;
    }
    i2s_write(I2S_NUM_0, i2s_buf, count * 2 * sizeof(int16_t), &written, portMAX_DELAY);
  }
}

void setup() {
  i2s_config_t cfg = {
    .mode                 = (i2s_mode_t)(I2S_MODE_MASTER | I2S_MODE_TX),
    .sample_rate          = SAMPLE_RATE,
    .bits_per_sample      = I2S_BITS_PER_SAMPLE_16BIT,
    .channel_format       = I2S_CHANNEL_FMT_RIGHT_LEFT,
    .communication_format = I2S_COMM_FORMAT_STAND_I2S,
    .intr_alloc_flags     = ESP_INTR_FLAG_LEVEL1,
    .dma_buf_count        = 8,
    .dma_buf_len          = 64,
    .use_apll             = false,
    .tx_desc_auto_clear   = true,
  };
  i2s_pin_config_t pins = {
    .bck_io_num   = I2S_BCLK,
    .ws_io_num    = I2S_LRCLK,
    .data_out_num = I2S_DOUT,
    .data_in_num  = I2S_PIN_NO_CHANGE,
  };
  i2s_driver_install(I2S_NUM_0, &cfg, 0, NULL);
  i2s_set_pin(I2S_NUM_0, &pins);

  for (int i = 0; i < PLAYLIST_LEN; i++) {
    playClip(clips[playlist[i]]);
    delay(500);
  }
}

void loop() { }`}</code></pre>
      <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-why">
      <strong>How the index works</strong>
      <code>playlist[i]</code> is a number pointing to a position in the <code>clips[]</code> array. <code>0</code> = clip1, <code>1</code> = clip2, <code>2</code> = clip3. Repeat an index to play that clip more than once. The example <code>{ 0, 1, 0, 2, 1 }</code> plays: clip1, clip2, clip1 again, clip3, clip2 again.
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-tip">
      <strong>Loop continuously?</strong>
      Move the <code>for</code> loop and <code>delay</code> into <code>loop()</code> instead of <code>setup()</code> - the playlist repeats forever.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Troubleshooting -->
  <div class="section" id="troubleshooting">
    <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
    <div class="trouble-item">
      <h3>Linker error: multiple definition of &lsquo;audio_data&rsquo;</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Two header files are using the same variable name. Each clip must have a unique <code>var_name</code> when you run <code>wav_to_i2s_header.py</code> - check that you passed a different third argument for each clip.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="trouble-item">
      <h3>Sketch too large - won&rsquo;t fit in flash</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Switch to the Huge APP partition scheme in Arduino IDE under Tools &rarr; Partition Scheme. This gives around 1.2MB for your sketch and clips combined.</li>
        <li>Drop the sample rate: re-convert your clips with <code>-ar 22050</code> in ffmpeg and update <code>SAMPLE_RATE</code> in the sketch. Speech stays clear at 22050Hz and clips are half the size.</li>
        <li>Trim clips shorter - every second at 44100Hz 16-bit mono is ~86KB.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="trouble-item">
      <h3>Compile error: &lsquo;clip1_data&rsquo; was not declared in this scope</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>The <code>#include</code> line at the top of the sketch doesn&rsquo;t match the <code>.h</code> filename you generated. Check that <code>clip1.h</code> is in your sketch folder and that the filename in the <code>#include</code> matches exactly.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

